# Post-Quantum Wallet System — Analysis & Recommendation for Zephyria

## Current State

Zephyria currently uses the **Ethereum-compatible crypto stack**:

| Component | Current | Where Used |
|---|---|---|
| User wallets (EOA) | **secp256k1 ECDSA** → Keccak256 → 20-byte address | [eoa.zig](file:///Users/karan/sol2zig/src/core/accounts/eoa.zig) |
| P2P shred signing | **Ed25519** (64-byte sig, 32-byte pubkey) | [shred_verifier.zig](file:///Users/karan/sol2zig/src/p2p/shred_verifier.zig) |
| Consensus aggregation | **BLS12-381** (aggregate sigs) | [src/crypto/blst/](file:///Users/karan/sol2zig/src/crypto/blst) |
| TX validation | secp256k1 `r,s,v` recovery → EIP-155 | [security.zig](file:///Users/karan/sol2zig/src/core/security.zig) |

**All three** of these primitives (ECDSA, Ed25519, BLS) are **broken by Shor's algorithm** on a sufficiently large quantum computer.

---

## NIST-Standardized Post-Quantum Signature Schemes

### 1. ML-DSA (FIPS 204) — formerly CRYSTALS-Dilithium

The **primary NIST recommendation** for general-purpose PQ signatures. Lattice-based (Module-LWE).

| Parameter Set | Security Level | Public Key | Private Key | Signature | Keygen | Sign | Verify |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **ML-DSA-44** | Level 2 (128-bit) | **1,312 B** | 2,560 B | **2,420 B** | ~0.05 ms | ~0.15 ms | **0.05 ms** |
| **ML-DSA-65** | Level 3 (192-bit) | **1,952 B** | 4,032 B | **3,309 B** | ~0.08 ms | ~0.25 ms | **0.08 ms** |
| **ML-DSA-87** | Level 5 (256-bit) | **2,592 B** | 4,896 B | **4,627 B** | ~0.12 ms | ~0.35 ms | **0.14 ms** |

**Pros:** NIST primary standard, simple implementation (modular arithmetic only), constant-time implementation straightforward, no floating-point needed, fastest verification. An optimized variant **ML-DSA-B** (Oct 2025) with BLAKE3 offers **+20% signing / +30% verification** speed.

**Cons:** Large signatures (2.4–4.6 KB per TX) — at 1M TPS that's **2.4 GB/s** of signature data alone for ML-DSA-44. Public keys are 1.3 KB+, far too large for direct use as addresses.

---

### 2. FN-DSA (FIPS 206) — formerly FALCON

Lattice-based (NTRU lattices), optimized for **compact signatures**. Standardized 2025.

| Parameter Set | Security Level | Public Key | Private Key | Signature | Keygen | Sign | Verify |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **FN-DSA-512** | Level 1 (128-bit) | **897 B** | 1,281 B | **666 B** | ~8 ms | ~0.3 ms | **0.04 ms** |
| **FN-DSA-1024** | Level 5 (256-bit) | **1,793 B** | 2,305 B | **1,280 B** | ~25 ms | ~0.6 ms | **0.08 ms** |

**Pros:** **Smallest signatures** of all NIST-standardized lattice schemes (~666 bytes vs 2,420 for ML-DSA-44). Fast signing and ultra-fast verification. Best fit for blockchain where every TX carries a signature.

**Cons:** Uses floating-point FFT for signing — harder to implement in constant-time, potential side-channel concerns. Slow key generation (~8ms). More complex implementation than ML-DSA.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> FN-DSA-512's **666-byte signature** is **~9x larger** than secp256k1's 65-byte signature, but **~3.6x smaller** than ML-DSA-44's 2,420-byte signature. For a blockchain targeting 1M TPS, this difference is enormous: **666 MB/s vs 2.4 GB/s** of signature bandwidth.

---

### 3. SLH-DSA (FIPS 205) — formerly SPHINCS+

Stateless **hash-based** signatures. Security relies only on hash function properties (most conservative assumption).

| Parameter Set | Security | Public Key | Private Key | Signature |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| SLH-DSA-128f | Level 1 | 32 B | 64 B | **17,088 B** |
| SLH-DSA-128s | Level 1 | 32 B | 64 B | **7,856 B** |
| SLH-DSA-256f | Level 5 | 64 B | 128 B | **49,856 B** |

**Pros:** Most conservative security assumptions (hash-based, well-understood). Tiny keys. Immune to lattice-specific attacks.

**Cons:** **Enormous signatures** (7–49 KB). Extremely slow signing. Completely impractical for high-TPS blockchain transactions.

> [!CAUTION]
> SLH-DSA is **not viable** for transaction signatures at any performance target. At 1M TPS with SLH-DSA-128s, you'd need **7.8 TB/s** of signature bandwidth. Suitable only as a fallback for root-of-trust / code-signing scenarios.

---

### 4. SQIsign (NIST Additional Signatures — Round 2)

Isogeny-based. **Smallest PQ signatures known**, but not yet standardized.

| Parameter Set | Security | Public Key | Signature | Sign Time | Verify Time |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| SQIsign-I | Level 1 | **65 B** | **148 B** | ~100 ms | ~5 ms |
| SQIsign-V | Level 5 | **129 B** | **292 B** | ~800 ms | ~40 ms |

**Pros:** Astonishingly compact — 148-byte signatures are only **2.3x** the size of secp256k1 (64 bytes). Feels like classical crypto in terms of sizes.

**Cons:** Not standardized yet (NIST Round 2). Extremely slow signing (~100ms per signature). Verification is passable but 100x slower than FN-DSA. Isogeny crypto is young; recent SIDH attacks raised concerns about the broader family. **Not production-ready.**

---

## Comparison Matrix for Blockchain Use

| Criterion | secp256k1 (current) | FN-DSA-512 | ML-DSA-44 | SQIsign-I | SLH-DSA-128s |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Quantum-Safe** | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| **Signature Size** | 65 B | **666 B** | 2,420 B | 148 B | 7,856 B |
| **Public Key Size** | 33/65 B | 897 B | 1,312 B | 65 B | 32 B |
| **Verify Speed** | ~0.1 ms | **~0.04 ms** | ~0.05 ms | ~5 ms | ~1 ms |
| **Sign Speed** | ~0.1 ms | ~0.3 ms | ~0.15 ms | ~100 ms | ~50 ms |
| **Bandwidth at 1M TPS** | 65 MB/s | **666 MB/s** | 2,420 MB/s | 148 MB/s | 7,856 MB/s |
| **NIST Standardized** | N/A (pre-Q) | ✅ (FIPS 206) | ✅ (FIPS 204) | ❌ (Round 2) | ✅ (FIPS 205) |
| **Impl Complexity** | Low | Medium | **Low** | High | Low |
| **Aggregate-able** | ❌ | With Squirrel | With Squirrel | ❌ | ❌ |

